WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.840
My name is Eric Cronstrom with the Center for Charter Schools at Central Michigan University.

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:17.280
I'm going to tell you a story about my first project after joining the Center.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.520
Now, this project was a challenge, but we were able to automate a process that had been performed

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:29.120
manually for more than a decade. On its own, the project was successful, but we turned it

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:33.840
into an opportunity to rethink how the organization approaches data science.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:40.320
This is a story about the technology and the techniques we used to automate a task

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:47.200
that seemed too complex for procedural document generation. But more importantly, this is a story

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:53.200
about how to make a difference in an organization, about how to build trust and convince leadership

00:00:53.200 --> 00:01:02.080
to try the new thing. One of the responsibilities we have as a charter school authorizer is to hold

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:05.919
our partner schools accountable for the academic performance of their students.

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:10.480
One of the ways we do this is with the Annual Performance Report.

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:19.120
The Annual Performance Report, or APR, is a document that summarizes how well students in

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:24.959
each of our 58 partner schools are doing academically. In the spirit of transparency,

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:31.040
these reports are made publicly available on the Center's website, and they're also distributed to

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:38.559
school boards and other stakeholders as print booklets. The organization demands high production

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:44.559
values for these documents, and they have to be absolutely correct. And to make no bones about it,

00:01:44.559 --> 00:01:51.519
they look good. And these publications are the primary responsibility of my new job.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:02:00.480
So try to picture yourself at a job interview. Across the table is your new potential boss.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:06.800
He's an impressive guy with a PhD in psychometrics. He's explaining how important

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:13.440
these reports are and some of what goes into making them. But there's a catch. These reports

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:20.559
that usually take months to produce have to go to print in seven weeks. Well, to quote Richard

00:02:20.559 --> 00:02:26.160
Branson, if someone offers you an amazing opportunity but you're not sure if you can do it,

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:34.320
say yes and learn how to do it later. So how do you make an APR? First things first,

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:41.360
you have to get your data. There are a variety of different sources. Individual test scores from

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:47.839
assessment vendors, student information from the Michigan Department of Ed, demographic and

00:02:47.839 --> 00:02:54.559
comparison data from the state and other public entities, and so on. Once you download everything,

00:02:54.559 --> 00:02:59.279
you load it into the database. Sometimes. Some of it just stays as flat files.

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:04.800
After sourcing all your information, you can start producing the visuals

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:12.960
with Excel. A school can have up to 23 different visualizations depending on the grade levels

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:18.720
offered. And there are nine different Excel templates that produce all of the charts and

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:25.360
graphs and tables required by the APRs. At this point, any data that actually made it into the

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:32.320
database gets pulled back out and copied into an Excel template. Then you manually output

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:39.919
the correct visuals for each school, validating the numbers as you go. One at a time for 23 visuals

00:03:39.919 --> 00:03:48.240
per school for 58 schools. Now the last link in this chain was Adobe InDesign, where the actual

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:53.919
documents get produced. There's a master report template that gets updated with fresh content

00:03:53.919 --> 00:04:00.000
every year. And finally, one last script pulls everything together to produce one PDF for each

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:08.639
school. This is where being a new person helps a bit. Hiring a new team member is an opportunity

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:14.960
to have a fresh set of eyes, who, like the proverbial boiled frog, knows right away when

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:20.640
they're dropped into hot water. Our tight deadline was also a blessing in disguise,

00:04:21.359 --> 00:04:26.000
since we knew there wasn't enough time to do things the way they had done before.

00:04:26.959 --> 00:04:33.359
So with only six weeks left at this point, we sat down in the conference room and hashed out our plan.

00:04:34.799 --> 00:04:41.040
This is a picture I took of the whiteboard after that meeting. We figured we had three different

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:47.279
potential paths forward. A fully automated solution built on R and rendering documents

00:04:47.279 --> 00:04:54.880
with R Markdown, or a hybrid solution where we render the visuals with R, but still use InDesign

00:04:54.959 --> 00:05:01.760
to pull the documents together. I should note that up until this point, nobody on the team,

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:08.559
myself included, had used much R. Excel was the tool of choice for data visualization,

00:05:09.119 --> 00:05:15.600
and most of any real analysis was performed in SAS. So we gave ourselves only a short amount

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:21.679
of time to experiment with R. And if we couldn't have a proof of concept for production-ready

00:05:21.679 --> 00:05:28.160
visuals in 10 days, we would use Excel. And if within a month we couldn't have an R Markdown

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:33.040
report that met our publication standards, we would use the InDesign templates.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:41.600
Like I said, I hadn't used much R up until this point. I was comfortable with programming.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:47.200
My background is in software development and automation. I had some exposure to R

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:52.640
just through my graduate coursework, but the only R Markdown reports I ever created were

00:05:53.440 --> 00:06:01.839
academic white papers. And looking back, I think it was this discussion about the risks involved

00:06:01.839 --> 00:06:08.000
and being open and honest about what I knew and what I didn't know and having a backup plan

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.079
is how I was able to convince the team to try something new. Now that we had a plan and we

00:06:14.079 --> 00:06:19.519
convinced the organization to let us experiment, we set out to recreate this report from the ground

00:06:19.519 --> 00:06:26.480
up. And the first thing we needed to do was prove to ourselves that we could create a publication

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:32.559
that adheres to our identity standards using R Markdown. And there was one issue that almost

00:06:32.559 --> 00:06:38.720
stopped us right away. So at this point in my career, I had been writing code professionally

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:45.040
for 10 years. I've taught web development courses. I've taught database design at a

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:52.559
graduate level. The single issue I spent the most time on for this report was getting a box

00:06:52.559 --> 00:06:59.359
with our CMU maroon background color with white text using a custom font in LaTeX.

00:07:01.359 --> 00:07:05.760
Maybe that just stands out as the most difficult technical challenge

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:11.040
because almost everything else was done with ggplot and ggplot is amazing.

00:07:12.079 --> 00:07:19.359
Regardless, it's not my proudest moment. More seriously though, the reason this process had

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:25.679
been performed manually for so long is that each school is a little different. Different schools

00:07:25.679 --> 00:07:32.640
offer different grade levels. Some of our schools are K through 12. Some are just high schools and

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:40.160
some are kindergarten through third grade. And beyond that, we evaluate the academic performance

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:46.720
of our schools based on the terms laid out in their individual contracts. The educational

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:53.440
goals of many of our schools are similar, but some are operating under unique circumstances

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:57.839
and all of those differences need to be represented in the annual performance report.

00:07:58.799 --> 00:08:04.880
When you're manually producing visuals in Excel, you can tweak things on the fly to accommodate

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:12.079
all those variations. Trying to automate around all that variability presents an interesting design

00:08:12.079 --> 00:08:20.320
challenge. There are two main strategies we employ to accommodate this, depending on the prevalence

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:27.200
of the variation and the impact that it has on the report. You can always write flow control logic

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:33.359
into your R code so your program will behave differently depending on what school's report

00:08:33.359 --> 00:08:40.719
is currently being rendered. This is okay if it's a unique situation that only impacts one or two

00:08:40.719 --> 00:08:49.760
schools, otherwise it can get out of hand quickly. What we try to do first is to generalize an issue

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:56.239
and develop a data structure that represents all possible variations. It effectively turns part of

00:08:56.239 --> 00:09:03.200
a school's contract into data. A good example of this is you can have two schools that both offer

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:10.640
instruction at grades K through 8. School A's contract stipulates they're to be evaluated on

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:17.039
the academic achievement of their students in grades 3 through 8. School B's contract

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:23.440
says they are to be evaluated based on their students in grades 3 through 7, excluding grade 8.

00:09:24.239 --> 00:09:29.359
Instead of a giant if-else chain in your code to keep track of all the contract grades,

00:09:29.359 --> 00:09:33.280
you can develop a data structure that represents that information.

00:09:35.359 --> 00:09:40.799
Going through this process, we identified more problems than we were able to fix right away.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.799
When you have an aggressive timeline, you do what you have to do to get the job done.

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:53.919
To be fair, we only gave ourselves six weeks to learn ggplot, markdown, and LaTeX.

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:59.599
Our code was never going to be pretty, but I'm proud of what we managed to accomplish.

00:10:00.799 --> 00:10:07.440
We met our deadline with a couple days to spare. The new fully automated reports look great.

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:13.200
With the push of a button, an R driver program renders one report per school

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:18.400
from a single R markdown template. And the best part is it's completely reproducible.

00:10:19.039 --> 00:10:23.520
Next year, we can push the same button again and get the same reports with updated data.

00:10:25.119 --> 00:10:29.599
That is, of course, until your communications department updates their brand identity

00:10:29.599 --> 00:10:35.520
standards with new fonts and new logos and new rules. Such is life.

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:41.520
So we sent our reports out to print on time, but we knew we weren't done.

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:48.080
We used success with R in this project to convince the organization to invest

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:55.280
more into our data infrastructure. We just wrapped up the implementation of our RStudio Connect

00:10:55.280 --> 00:11:01.280
server, and we have time carved out for research and development of dashboards and other analytics

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:08.320
projects. My next big project is a Plumber API that will feed data to a web app hosted on our

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:16.000
website. Gone are the days of juggling flat files between projects. Now I access data in my SQL

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:23.119
server directly using R with dbPlayer, which I'm convinced works on Blackmagic.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:31.840
Showing results is what convinced the organization to give us the time to invest in ourselves.

00:11:32.719 --> 00:11:37.599
We've started adopting best practices around data management and software development.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:45.280
Now all of the data that we use makes it into our data warehouse, and each data pipeline has an

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:52.479
automated integration services package. Because as it turns out, Excel was our ETL tool as well as

00:11:52.479 --> 00:11:59.520
our DataViz tool. And all of the code and assets needed to build each solution are stored in one

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:04.960
spot in source control. And we're able to spend more time building and doing work that we enjoy

00:12:05.599 --> 00:12:12.080
because exporting hundreds of charts from Excel one at a time is super boring. And we're able to

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:17.760
spend more time contributing research and at a time when research and education is critical.

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:23.520
I hope that our story helps inspire you to take on your next big project.

00:12:24.159 --> 00:12:28.479
Anyone, regardless of tenure or position or job title, can be a leader.

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:31.280
You just need to take the first step.

